(3254, 1, '2014-03-08 04:05:19', '2014-03-08 04:05:19', '[dt_sc_one_fourth first][dt_theme_service icon=''icon-skillset'' type=''custom'' title=''Target Skillsets''][/dt_theme_service][/dt_sc_one_fourth]\r\n[dt_sc_one_fourth][dt_theme_service icon=''icon-activity'' type=''custom'' title=''Extra Activities''][/dt_theme_service][/dt_sc_one_fourth]\r\n[dt_sc_one_fourth][dt_theme_service icon=''icon-track'' type=''custom'' title=''Complete Tracking''][/dt_theme_service][/dt_sc_one_fourth]\r\n[dt_sc_one_fourth][dt_theme_service icon=''icon-bus'' type=''custom'' title=''Individual Bus''][/dt_theme_service][/dt_sc_one_fourth]\r\n\r\n[dt_sc_hr_invisible]\r\n[dt_hr_title tag=''h2'']About our maple[/dt_hr_title]\r\n[dt_sc_tabs_vertical]\r\n[dt_sc_tab title="Maple Sugar" icon="fa-trophy"]\r\n<h3>From Syrup to Sugar</h3>\r\nThe process for making maple sugar is one that takes a very long time to make. It involved many years of planning where to best source all the syrup that comes from the trees.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Trees take sometimes up to 40 years before you can even tap the trees to harvest the liquid syrup. The trees release their sap in the period between March to April.</li>\r\n	<li>The syrup is then boiled to release all liquid and turn it into a crystallized form that can be made into granules.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/dt_sc_fancy_ul]\r\n[/dt_sc_tab]\r\n[dt_sc_tab title="History of Maple Syrup" icon="fa-male"]\r\nNative Americans were the first in the North America to tap trees and harvest syrup from them. They taught the Europeans who came here all about it. Aboriginal tribes practiced rituals around sugar-making, celebrating the Sugar Moon (the first <a title="Full moon" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Full_moon">full moon</a> of <a title="Spring (season)" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spring_%28season%29">spring</a>) with a Maple Dance. The <a title="Algonquian peoples" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algonquian_peoples">Algonquians</a> recognized maple sap as a source of energy and nutrition. At the beginning of the spring thaw, they used <a title="Stone tool" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stone_tool">stone tools</a> to make V-shaped incisions in tree trunks; they then inserted reeds or concave pieces of bark to run the sap into buckets, which were often made from birch bark.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-history_14-1"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maple_syrup#cite_note-history-14"><span>[</span>14<span>]</span></a></sup> The maple sap was concentrated either by dropping hot <a title="Outdoor cooking" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Outdoor_cooking">cooking stones</a> into the buckets<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-larkin_16-0"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maple_syrup#cite_note-larkin-16"><span>[</span>16<span>]</span></a></sup> or by leaving them exposed to the cold temperatures overnight and disposing of <a title="Fractional freezing" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fractional_freezing">the layer of ice</a> that formed on top. While there was widespread <a title="Agriculture in Mesoamerica" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Agriculture_in_Mesoamerica">Agriculture in Mesoamerica</a> and the Southeast and Southwest regions of the United States, the production of maple syrup is one of very few agricultural processes in the Northeast that did not come European colonists.\r\n[/dt_sc_tab]\r\n[dt_sc_tab title="Self Thinking Capabilities" icon="fa-key"]\r\nFusce nibh lacus, luctus sed purus pellentesque, hendrerit varius ante. Fusce vel augue erat. Aenean tempor urna quis auctor mollis. In mi lectus, lobortis gravida eros et, interdum vehicula lacus.\r\n\r\nInteger malesuada, leo eget porttitor placerat, est nibh porttitor sapien, et fringilla augue velit sed neque. Phasellus tempus blandit mauris sed hendrerit. Ut vel ipsum orci. Fusce eu sagittis metus. Mauris sed ipsum nisl.\r\n[/dt_sc_tab]\r\n[dt_sc_tab title="Bright Future" icon="fa-thumbs-o-up"]\r\nMorbi at massa auctor ipsum scelerisqu