(3301, 1, '2014-03-12 02:34:52', '2014-03-12 02:34:52', '[dt_sc_one_fourth first][dt_theme_service icon=''icon-skillset'' type=''custom'' title=''Pure Maple''][/dt_theme_service][/dt_sc_one_fourth] [dt_sc_one_fourth][dt_theme_service icon=''icon-activity'' type=''custom'' title=''Blueberry Maple Pancake''][/dt_theme_service][/dt_sc_one_fourth] [dt_sc_one_fourth][dt_theme_service icon=''icon-track'' type=''custom'' title=''Chocolate Fudge Maple''][/dt_theme_service][/dt_sc_one_fourth] [dt_sc_one_fourth][dt_theme_service icon=''icon-bus'' type=''custom'' title=''Dulce De Leche Maple''][/dt_theme_service][/dt_sc_one_fourth] [dt_sc_hr_invisible] [dt_hr_title tag=''h2'']About our maple[/dt_hr_title] [dt_sc_tabs_vertical] [dt_sc_tab title="Maple Sugar" icon="fa-trophy"]\r\n<h3>From Syrup to Sugar</h3>\r\nThe process for making maple sugar is one that takes a very long time to complete. These are some facts about how it is obtained.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Trees take sometimes up to 40 years before you can even tap the trees to harvest the liquid syrup. The trees release their sap in the period between March to April.</li>\r\n	<li><span class="userContent" data-ft="{&quot;tn&quot;:&quot;K&quot;}"><span class="text_exposed_show">A new tap hole must be made each year.</span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span class="userContent" data-ft="{&quot;tn&quot;:&quot;K&quot;}"><span class="text_exposed_show">Tapping doesn''t hurt the tree in any way  studies show the trees that are tapped year after year live just as long, and stay just as strong and healthy.</span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span class="userContent" data-ft="{&quot;tn&quot;:&quot;K&quot;}"><span class="text_exposed_show">The sap "runs" when the temperatures fall below freezing at night and then thaws during the day. The freezing point is 32 degrees F.</span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span class="userContent" data-ft="{&quot;tn&quot;:&quot;K&quot;}">Forty gallons of sap is gathered to make one gallon of maple syrup.</span></li>\r\n	<li><span class="userContent" data-ft="{&quot;tn&quot;:&quot;K&quot;}">Maple sugar is made by boiling the syrup longer, to reduce the water content and then stirring until a sugar is formed.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/dt_sc_tab] [dt_sc_tab title="History of Maple Syrup" icon="fa-male"] Native Americans were the first in the North America to tap trees and harvest syrup from them. They taught the Europeans who came here all about it. Aboriginal tribes practiced rituals around sugar-making, celebrating the Sugar Moon (the first <a title="Full moon" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Full_moon">full moon</a> of <a title="Spring (season)" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spring_%28season%29">spring</a>) with a Maple Dance. The <a title="Algonquian peoples" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algonquian_peoples">Algonquians</a> recognized maple sap as a source of energy and nutrition. At the beginning of the spring thaw, they used <a title="Stone tool" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stone_tool">stone tools</a> to make V-shaped incisions in tree trunks; they then inserted reeds or concave pieces of bark to run the sap into buckets, which were often made from birch bark.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-history_14-1"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maple_syrup#cite_note-history-14"><span>[</span>14<span>]</span></a></sup> The maple sap was concentrated either by dropping hot <a title="Outdoor cooking" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Outdoor_cooking">cooking stones</a> into the buckets<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-larkin_16-0"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maple_syrup#cite_note-larkin-16"><span>[</span>16<span>]</span></a></sup> or by leaving them exposed to the cold temperatures overnight and disposing of <a title="Fractional freezing" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fractional_freezing">the layer of ice</a> that formed on top. While there was widespread <a title="Agriculture in Mesoamerica" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Agriculture_in_Mesoamerica">Agriculture in Mesoamerica</a> and the Southeast and Southwest regions of the United States, the production of maple syrup is one of very few agricultural processes in the Northeast that did not come European colonists.\r\n\r\n[/dt_sc_tab] [dt_sc_tab title="Is it healthy?" icon="fa-key"]\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span class="userContent">Maple Syrup contains iron, potassium, magnesium &amp; phosphorus - and has a higher calcium content that milk; it also contains small amounts of amino acids, proteins &amp; vitamins B2, B5 &amp; niacin</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span class="userContent"> Maple Syru<span class="text_exposed_show">p only has 40 calories per Tablespoon. Honey has 45, white sugar has 55 &amp; corn sugar has 60.</span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span class="userContent"><span class="text_exposed_show"> Researchers have identified compounds in maple syrup with similar anti-inflammatory or anti-oxidant properties as blueberries, green tea and other superfoods</span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span class="userContent"><span class="text_exposed_show"> These compounds have been shown to fight cancer, diabetes and bacterial illnesses</span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span class="userContent"><span class="text_exposed_show"> Scientists have found that maple syrup''s natural phenols  potentially beneficial antioxidant compounds  inhibit two carbohydrate-hydrolyzing enzymes that are relevant to type 2 diabetes</span></span>[/dt_sc_tab]</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[dt_sc_tab title="Why Organic?" icon="fa-thumbs-o-up"] In an age with kids and adults that have serious health problems due to modern practices in nutrition one thing will always remain true. Nature does best what we humans fail at. It provides us with all we need if we are willing to work on it''s terms. Organic food is the healthiest option that can be provided and in our minds just plain old tastes better. Like have a nice home made meal![/dt_sc_tab] [dt_sc_tab title="Where can you find us?" icon="fa-plane"] We will be doing events all over Miami! Our event calendar lists where we will be and how you can find us. Please come try this amazing treat from the north that keeps you coming back for more![/dt_sc_tab] [/dt_sc_tabs_vertical] [dt_sc_hr_invisible] [dt_hr_title tag=''h2'']Our Gallery[/dt_hr_title] [dt_gallery_carousel limit=''8'' posts_design=''shape-one'' /] [dt_sc_hr_invisible] [dt_hr_title tag=''h2'']Recent Blog[/dt_hr_title] [dt_blog_posts posts_column=''one-half-column'' limit=''2'' excerpt_length=''20'' categories=''6''] [dt_sc_hr_invisible] [dt_hr_title tag=''h2'']Meet our Team[/dt_hr_title] [dt_sc_one_fourth first] [dt_sc_team name="Matthew Ondusko" image="http://placehold.it/460x460&amp;text=Team1" role="Co-Owner" twitter="#" skype="#" facebook="#"/] [/dt_sc_one_fourth] [dt_sc_one_fourth] [dt_sc_team name="Ricky Semancik" image="http://placehold.it/460x460&amp;text=Team2" role="Co-Owner" skype="#" facebook="#" linkedin="#"/] [/dt_sc_one_fourth] [dt_sc_one_fourth] [dt_sc_team name="Andreea Iosub" image="http://placehold.it/460x460&amp;text=Team3" role="Support" twitter="#" skype="#" facebook="#"/] [/dt_sc_one_fourth] [dt_sc_one_fourth] [dt_sc_team name="Randi Shannon" image="http://placehold.it/460x460&amp;text=Team4" role="Franchise Manager" twitter="#" facebook="#" flickr="#"/] [/dt_sc_one_fourth] [dt_sc_hr_invisible]', 'Home Page II', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '2992-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-03-12 02:34:52', '2014-03-12 02:34:52', '', 2992, 'http://www.fluffymaplepuffpuffs.com/uncategorized/2992-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
