(3500, 1, '2014-04-25 21:15:56', '2014-04-25 21:15:56', '<code></code>[dt_sc_one_fourth first][dt_theme_service icon=''icon-skillset'' type=''custom'' title=''Pure Maple''][/dt_theme_service][/dt_sc_one_fourth] [dt_sc_one_fourth][dt_theme_service icon=''icon-activity'' type=''custom'' title=''Blueberry Maple Pancake''][/dt_theme_service][/dt_sc_one_fourth] [dt_sc_one_fourth][dt_theme_service icon=''icon-track'' type=''custom'' title=''Chocolate Fudge Maple''][/dt_theme_service][/dt_sc_one_fourth] [dt_sc_one_fourth][dt_theme_service icon=''icon-bus'' type=''custom'' title=''Strawberry Maple''][/dt_theme_service][/dt_sc_one_fourth] [dt_sc_hr_invisible] [dt_hr_title tag=''h2'']About our maple[/dt_hr_title] [dt_sc_tabs_vertical] [dt_sc_tab title="Maple Sugar" icon="fa-trophy"]\r\n<h3>From Syrup to Sugar</h3>\r\nThe process for making maple sugar is one that takes a very long time to complete. These are some facts about how it is obtained.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Trees take sometimes up to 40 years before you can even tap the trees to harvest the liquid syrup. The trees release their sap in the period between March to April.</li>\r\n	<li><span class="userContent" data-ft="{&quot;tn&quot;:&quot;K&quot;}"><span class="text_exposed_show">A new tap hole must be made each year.</span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span class="userContent" data-ft="{&quot;tn&quot;:&quot;K&quot;}"><span class="text_exposed_show">Tapping doesn''t hurt the tree in any way  studies show the trees that are tapped year after year live just as long, and stay just as strong and healthy.</span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span class="userContent" data-ft="{&quot;tn&quot;:&quot;K&quot;}"><span class="text_exposed_show">The sap "runs" when the temperatures fall below freezing at night and then thaws during the day. The freezing point is 32 degrees F.</span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span class="userContent" data-ft="{&quot;tn&quot;:&quot;K&quot;}">Forty gallons of sap is gathered to make one gallon of maple syrup.</span></li>\r\n	<li><span class="userContent" data-ft="{&quot;tn&quot;:&quot;K&quot;}">Maple sugar is made by boiling the syrup longer, to reduce the water content and then stirring until a sugar is formed.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/dt_sc_tab] [dt_sc_tab title="<strong>History of Maple Syrup</strong>" icon="fa-male"] Early settlers in the U.S. Northeast and Canada learned about sugar maples from Native Americans. While there are written accounts of maple sugaring in North America dating back to 1557, the exact origins of sugaring are unknown. Various legends exist to explain the initial discovery. One is that the chief of a tribe threw a tomahawk at a tree, sap ran out and his wife boiled venison in the liquid. Another version holds that Native Americans stumbled on sap running from a broken maple branch.\r\nHistory also remains silent on whether Native Americans boiled down the sap to maple sugar, or if these techniques were introduced by the French explorers and missionaries. But by the 1700s, Native Americans and European settlers alike were using iron and copper kettles to make syrup and sugar. In 1755, a young colonist was captured and "adopted" by a small group of natives in the region that is now Ohio. In 1799 he published his story, in which he included a description of how the Native Americans made maple sugar.\r\nIn the late 1700s and early 1800s, maple sap was produced into maple sugar, a granular, solid block of maple that had a long shelf-life and could be easily transported. Maple sugar was promoted by the Quakers and abolitionists as an alternative to West Indian slave-produced cane sugar; Thomas Jefferson even started a maple plantation at Monticello in 1791.\r\nIt wasnt until the Civil War that the maple syrup industry was born, with the introduction of the tin cans and the invention of metal spouts and evaporator pans. Most early producers were dairy farmers who made maple syrup and sugar during the off-season of the farm for their own use and for extra income.\r\nTechnology remain largely the same for the next century until the energy crisis of the 1970s forced maple syrup producers to change their labor-intensive process. With another surge of technological breakthroughs, tubing systems were perfected, taking the sap directly from the tree to the sugarhouse. Vacuum pumps were added to the tubing systems, pre-heaters were developed to "recycle" heat lost in the steam, and reverse-osmosis filters were designed to take a portion of the water out of the sap before it was boiled. And these technological advances continue today, ever moving the story of maple syrup forward.\r\n\r\n	<li><span class="userContent">Maple Syrup contains iron, potassium, magnesium &amp; phosphorus - and has a higher calcium content that milk; it also contains small amounts of amino acids, proteins &amp; vitamins B2, B5 &amp; niacin</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span class="userContent"> Maple Syru<span class="text_exposed_show">p only has 40 calories per Tablespoon. Honey has 45, white sugar has 55 &amp; corn sugar has 60.</span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span class="userContent"><span class="text_exposed_show"> Researchers have identified compounds in maple syrup with similar anti-inflammatory or anti-oxidant properties as blueberries, green tea and other superfoods</span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span class="userContent"><span class="text_exposed_show"> These compounds have been shown to fight cancer, diabetes and bacterial illnesses</span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span class="userContent"><span class="text_exposed_show"> Scientists have found that maple syrup''s natural phenols  potentially beneficial antioxidant compounds  inhibit two carbohydrate-hydrolyzing enzymes that are relevant to type 2 diabetes</span></span>[/dt_sc_tab]</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[dt_sc_tab title="Why Organic?" icon="fa-thumbs-o-up"]Awesome info on why organic maple syrup is so much better than non-organic:\r\n\r\nProducing organic maple syrup involves the respect of the environment, trees and the ecosystem of the maple bush. Producing organic maple syrup also involves respecting organic certification standards in processing the sap:\r\n\r\n-No chemical fertilizers, pesticides, phytocides, etc. are used in the maple bush or in the area where organic products are processed. If necessary, agricultural lime, wood ash or natural fertilizers may be used.\r\n-There is a limit of three tapholes are done per tree. No over-tapping. No germicides (paraformaldehyde) in tapholes.\r\n-Selective and correct use of vacuum tubing\r\n-Avoid at all times frequent use of machinery to prevent injury to the surfaced roots.\r\n\r\nOrganic certification standards in the processing of the sap:\r\n\r\n<li>There is no lead or lead solder used in the equipment required for processing organic maple products,consequently, there is no lead in the finished product. Lead can be a concern with some conventional maple syrup producers using older equipment. </li>\r\n<li>During the running season, the line system must be cleaned with natural biodegradable products.\r\n-No synthetic chemical products are used to control foam during boiling. Instead, certified organic and Montreal Kosher vegetable anti-foaming agent is used, such as safflower oil.\r\n-No treatment of sap with ultra-violet radiation. No microwave cooking of processed organic maple products. -The maple syrup is strained though a fine polyethylene membrane\r\n-Maple syrup is stores in stainless steel, instead of galvanized steel drums.\r\n-Each bottle of organic maple syrup is traceable. Using the lot #, one is able to determine the manufacturer is, and when the syrup was produced [/dt_sc_tab] [dt_sc_tab title="Where can you find us?" icon="fa-plane"] We will be doing events all over Miami! Our event calendar lists where we will be and how you can find us. Please come try this amazing treat from the north that keeps you coming back for more![/dt_sc_tab] [/dt_sc_tabs_vertical] [dt_sc_hr_invisible] [dt_hr_title tag=''h2'']Our Gallery[/dt_hr_title] [dt_gallery_carousel limit=''8'' posts_design=''shape-one'' /] [dt_sc_hr_invisible] [dt_hr_title tag=''h2'']Recent Blog[/dt_hr_title] [dt_blog_posts posts_column=''one-half-column'' limit=''2'' excerpt_length=''20'' categories=''6''] [dt_sc_hr_invisible] [dt_hr_title tag=''h2'']Meet our Team[/dt_hr_title] [dt_sc_one_fourth first] [dt_sc_team name="Matthew Ondusko" image="http://placehold.it/460x460&amp;text=Matt" role="Co-Owner" twitter="#" instagram="#" facebook="#"/] [/dt_sc_one_fourth] [dt_sc_one_fourth] [dt_sc_team name="Randi Shannon" image="http://placehold.it/460x460&amp;text=Randi" role="Co-Owner" twitter="#" instagram="#" facebook="#"/] [/dt_sc_one_fourth] [dt_sc_hr_invisible]', 'Home', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '2992-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-04-25 21:15:56', '2014-04-25 21:15:56', '', 2992, 'http://www.fluffymaplepuffpuffs.com/uncategorized/2992-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
